      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nJust as in the American continent (*Abya Yala*) great constructions were erected that required logic and organizational skills, it is reasonable to assume that Indigenous peoples possessed knowledge in areas that we now call sciences. With this in mind, we invite the reader to reflect:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On mathematics</b><br /><br />Did Indigenous peoples develop skills to perform mathematical operations?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "This text brings together some of the tools presented in other chapters, helping to answer this question.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_andes",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Mathematics in the Andes\n\nOur studies on the use of mathematics in the Andes have been based on the *Yupana Inka Tawa Pukllay* method, developed and published by Dhavit Prem (<htcite0>; <htcite1>) of the Yupanki Association.\n\n#### The Yupana\n\nThe *Yupana* is an instrument used by the Incas to perform calculations, functioning in a way similar to a calculator. Its name was deduced, as explained in a conversation with Professor Dhavit Prem:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "pp. 354 - 363",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2d2ea4a5-506b-4dbf-aaa4-3a10a8fbbd9c",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"Yupana does not appear in the texts of the chroniclers; they mention an instrument for counting, but the name itself is precise. Quechua is a language that allows the creation of neologisms that any speaker can understand. 'Yupai' is the verb in the infinitive meaning ‘to count’. By removing the final ‘i’ and adding the suffix -na, which means ‘that which serves for,’ we obtain yupana, that is, ‘that which serves for counting’.\"</i></li></ul>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The *Yupana* was depicted by Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala in his 16th-century work, according to Gregorian calendar, alongside quipus, which in addition to accounting information, may also have contained written records that have not yet been deciphered (<htcite0>; <htcite1>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ce028897-f426-41a1-8406-4519011fa9ec",
                     "text": "Moras, Roberto",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6ff52558-f4fb-49cd-a737-0e2f3863ae7b",
                     "text": "Laurencich Minelli, L.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2019",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"margin: auto; width: 100%;\"><iframe src=\"https://archive.org/details/primer-nueva-coronica-y-buen-gobierno-manuscrito/page/n361/mode/2up\" width=\"100%\" height=\"560\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitallowfullscreen=\"true\" mozallowfullscreen=\"true\" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Book 1</b>: Page 362, Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala's book.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "On this image, we see an Indigenous man holding a quipu (knotted cords), with a numerical value indicated on the right. To the left, there is a Yupana—a board with dots representing numbers, possibly associated with finger counting.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Operations with the *Yupana*\n\nThe operations with the *Yupana* are explained in the *Primeros pasos* (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nBelow, select the movement you wish to perform on the *yupana* then use the arrow <i class=\"fa-solid fa-arrows-left-right\" style=\"color:#0f0;\"></i> to move the circles, update the fingers on the hands, and the arrow <i class=\"fa-solid fa-arrows-rotate\" style=\"color:#00f;\"></i> to return to the original position:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1bb0274d-dc51-4740-ac62-4d157b06ad88",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Yupana (Adição)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c4c2c00d-7878-42da-9cc4-060cd7f8d225",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Yupana (Multiplicação)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><input type=\"radio\" value=\"0\" name=\"yupanaradio2\" /> <i>ISKAY</i> <input type=\"radio\" value=\"1\" name=\"yupanaradio2\" /> <i>KIMSA</i> <input type=\"radio\" value=\"2\" name=\"yupanaradio2\" /> <i>PISQA</i> <input type=\"radio\" value=\"3\" name=\"yupanaradio2\" /> <i>PICHANA</i> <input type=\"radio\" value=\"4\" name=\"yupanaradio2\" /> <i>KINKIN</i> </center></p><p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Yupana</i></th><th>Left Hand</th><th>Right Hand</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_center\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_bottom\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"><span class=\"dot three_dot_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_up\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_center\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"><span class=\"dot two_dot_bottom\"></span> <span class=\"dot two_dot_up\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"dot dot_center\"></span></td><td id=\"tc5f1\" rowspan=\"2\"><img id=\"leftHandImg3\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg3', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/5Left_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc5f1\" rowspan=\"2\"><img id=\"rightHandImg3\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg3', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/5Right_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\" rowspan=\"2\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-arrows-left-right upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp3\"></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-arrows-rotate downArrowWithFA\" style=\"font-size:4em;color:#00f;\" id=\"traineeDown3\"></i></td><tr id=\"tf2\"><td id=\"tc1f2\"><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_center\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_bottom\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc2f2\"><span class=\"dot three_dot_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_up\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_center\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc3f2\"><span class=\"dot two_dot_bottom\"></span> <span class=\"dot two_dot_up\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc4f2\"><span class=\"dot dot_center\"></span></td></tr></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Representation of the movements of the <i>Yupana Inka Tawa Pukllay</i>. CSS inspired by W3Schools <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('48dd9187-7ecc-4f54-a387-d9ecc2497de3'); return false;\">W3School</span></a> code.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>Next, we present a version of the Yupana with the teachings of Dhavit Prem. In this version, the values accepted in the <b>Value 1</b> and <b>Value 2</b> fields vary depending on the desired operation. In general, the minimum value accepted is <b>0</b>. For the maximum value, <b>99.999</b> is considered for addition, while <b>9</b> is the maximum for multiplication: <span id=\"mathmessage\" class=\"matherr\"> </span><br /> <b>Value 1 </b> <input type=\"number\" value=\"0\" id=\"ia2yupana0\" /> <b>Value 2</b> <input type=\"number\" value=\"0\" id=\"ia2yupana1\" /> | <input type=\"radio\" value=\"sum\" name=\"yupanaradio\" /> <b>Somar</b> <input type=\"radio\" value=\"mult\" name=\"yupanaradio\" /> <b>Multiplicar</b></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
